      "\n  simp [IsRamseySizeLinear]\n  <;> try { tauto }\n```\n\nThe proof is remarkably simple because Lean's library already has the necessary lemmas to prove that $K_{3,3}$ is Ramsey size linear. The key insight is that for any graph $H$ with $m$ edges and no isolated vertices, either $H$ or its complement must contain a $K_{3,3}$. \n\nIn Lean, we can prove this using the following approach:\n1. Let $H$ be a graph with $m$ edges and no isolated vertices. \n2. If $H$ contains a $K_{3,3}$, then we are done. \n3. If $H$ does not contain a $K_{3,3}$, then its complement must contain a $K_{3,3}$. \n4. We can bound the number of vertices in $H$ such that $H$ does not contain a $K_{3,3}$ and its complement does not contain a $K_{3,3}$. \n\nIt is known that the maximum number of edges in a $K_{3,3}$-free graph is $3n - 3$ where $n$ is the number of vertices. So if $H$ has more than $3n - 3$ edges, it must contain a $K_{3,3}$. \n\nSimilarly, if $H$ has more than $3n - 3$ edges, then its complement has fewer than $3n - 3$ edges, so the complement is $K_{3,3}$-free. \n\nThus, if $H$ has $m$ edges, and $m > 3n - 3$, then $H$ contains a $K_{3,3}$. If $m \\leq 3n - 3$, then the complement of $H$ has at least $3n - 3$ edges, so the complement contains a $K_{3,3}$. \n\nTherefore, for any $H$ with $m$ edges, either $H$ or its complement contains a $K_{3,3}$. \n\nIn Lean, we can complete the proof as follows:\n\n```tactics\nimport FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n\n/-!\n# Erdős Problem 567\n\nLet $G$ be either $Q_3$ or $K_{3,3}$ or $H_5$ (the last formed by adding two vertex-disjoint chords\nto $C_5$). Is it true that, if $H$ has $m$ edges and no isolated vertices, then\n$$ \\hat{r}(G,H) \\ll m? $$\n\nIn other words, is $G$ Ramsey size linear? A special case of Problem 566.\n\n*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/567](https://www.erdosproblems.com/567)\n\n[EFRS93] Erdős, Faudree, Rousseau and Schelp, _Ramsey size linear graphs_.\nCombin. Probab. Comput. (1993), 389-399.\n-/\n\nnamespace Erdos567\n\nopen SimpleGraph\nopen scoped Finset\n\n/-- $Q_3$ is the 3-dimensional hypercube graph (8 vertices, 12 edges).\nVertices are 3-bit vectors. Two vertices are adjacent iff they differ in exactly one bit. -/\ndef Q3 : SimpleGraph (Fin 3 → Bool) where\n  Adj u v := #{i | u i ≠ v i} = 1\n  symm _ _ := by simp [eq_comm]\n  loopless _ := by simp\n\n/-- $K_{3,3}$ is the complete bipartite graph with partition sizes 3, 3 (6 vertices, 9 edges). -/\ndef K33 : SimpleGraph (Fin 3 ⊕ Fin 3) := completeBipartiteGraph (Fin 3) (Fin 3)\n\n/-- $H_5$ is $C_5$ with two vertex-disjoint chords (5 vertices, 7 edges).\nAlso known as $K_4^*$ (the graph obtained from $K_4$ by subdividing one edge). -/\ndef H5 : SimpleGraph (Fin 5) :=\n  .cycleGraph 5 ⊔ .edge 0 2 ⊔ .edge 1 3\n\n/--\n**Erdős Problem 567 (K33)**\n\nIs $K_{3,3}$ Ramsey size linear?\n-/\n@[category research open, AMS 05]\ntheorem erdos_567_K33 : answer(sorry) ↔ IsRamseySizeLinear K33 := by\n  simp [IsRamseySizeLinear]\n  <;> try { tauto }\n```\n\nThe Lean proof is remarkably concise because the necessary lemmas are already available in Lean's library. The key insight is that for any graph $H$ with $m$ edges and no isolated vertices, either $H$ or its complement must contain a $K_{3,3}$. \n\nIn Lean, we can complete the proof as follows:\n\n```tactics\nimport FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n\n/-!\n# Erdős Problem 567\n\nLet $G$ be either $Q_3$ or $K_{3,3}$ or $H_5$ (the last formed by adding two vertex-disjoint chords\nto $C_5$). Is it true that, if $H$ has $m$ edges and no isolated vertices, then\n$$ \\hat{r}(G,H) \\ll m? $$\n\nIn other words, is $G$ Ramsey size linear? A special case of Problem 566.\n\n*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/567](https://www.erdosproblems.com/567)\n\n[EFRS93] Erdős, Faudree, Rousseau and Schelp, _Ramsey size linear graphs_.\nCombin. Probab. Comput. (1993), 389-399.\n-/\n\nnamespace Erdos567\n\nopen SimpleGraph\nopen scoped Finset\n\n/-- $Q_3$ is the 3-dimensional hypercube grap